<TITLE> Dhaka assured of extradition of Mujib killers: Sahara </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 17 (bdnews24.com)Dhaka has been assured of cooperation from the countries, where the self-confessed killers of independence hero Sheikh Mujibur Rahman have been hiding, for extradition, the home minister said on Saturday. "We have also sought assistance from the Interpol to bring back convicted and absconding killers who have been hiding in many countries," Sahara Khatun told reporters at ZIA on Saturday night. She returned home after attending the Interpol's 78th general session in Singapore. "During discussion with minister-level officials of different countries I personally have sought their assistance to bring back the killers home and they have also assured me." "The Interpol has also issued red notices against them. "Talks have been held with the UN undersecretary and the Interpol president on the issue. We hope this initiative will succeed." "In addition, I have taken up the issue with the Interpol session as well." Home secretary Abdus Sobhan and inspector general of police Noor Mohammad, among others, were present at the media briefing. Sahara left for Singapore Oct 10. Apart from Interpol president Khoo Boon Hui and secretary general Ronald K Noble, heads of the 187 countries' police along with minister-level officials and UN representatives attended the event. Independence hero 'Bangabandhu' Sheikh Mujibur Rahman was killed along with his family members on Aug 15, 1975. After the Awami League government came to power in 1996 a case was filed with Dhanmondi Police Station against 24 persons. On Nov 8, 1998, Dhaka sessions judge Golam Rasul awarded death sentences to 15 of the 20 accused. Four of the convicts major (retd) Bazlul Huda, Lt Col (dismissed) Syed Faruk Rahman, Lt Col (retd) Sultan Shahriar Rashid Khan and Lt Col (retd) Mohiuddin Ahmed appealed to the High Court against the verdict. On Dec 14, 2000 the High Court gave a split verdict in the caseJustice Md Ruhul Amin upheld death sentences of 10 of the convicts but Justice ABM Khairul Haque retained death sentences of all 15. On April 30, 2001 Justice Mohammad Fazlul Karim of a third High Court bench upheld death sentences of 12 and acquitted three. The freshly formed five-member bench headed by Justice Mohammed Tafazzal Islam began hearing the appeals by death convicts on Oct 5. Of those having received death sentence, former Lt Col Abdur Rashid, Lt Col Shariful Haq Dalim, Lt Col Noor, Risalder Moslemuddin, Lt Col Rashed Chowdhury and Capt Majed are absconding. Absconding convict Aziz Pasha died in exile in Zimbabwe. bd
